<HEADLINE>
<P>
U.S. WORLD ROLE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Your editorials on foreign policy and the U.N. (Nov. 20, 27, Dec. 4, 11) are 
indeed erudite, comprehensive and coherent, with extensive quotation from 
foreign affairs experts. Your support for a rapid deployment force and its 
functional operation reflects a continuation of a Cold War and colonial policy 
of solving conflicts by military intervention.There is ample evidence of the 
failures of these missions. Ethnic, religious and class conflicts have been 
pandered to, regional harmony and stability shattered, democracies crushed, 
repressive regimes endured and alliances formed in the wake of the Cold War, as 
a part of global strategy. 
</P>
<P>
 The present constitution of the Security Council is undemocratic and 
unrepresentative; it must include more countries from Asia, South America and 
Africa like Japan, India, Brazil and Nigeria. The role of the U.N. should be 
confined to the areas of health, culture, art, economics, trade, education, 
food and terrorism. 
</P>
<P>
 Your suggestion of U.S. military intervention in combatting regional conflict 
or violation of human rights is also not sound unless the security and vital 
interests of the U.S. are threatened. The economy and high standards of ethics 
should be the future direction in the post-Cold War era. 
</P>
<P>
 NIRODE C. MOHANTY 
</P>
<P>
 Huntington Beach 
</P>
</TEXT>
