<LENGTH>
<P>
243 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
HOLIDAY PICK OF THE WEEK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RANDY LEWIS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Ben Keith & Friends 
</P>
<P>
 "Seven Gates" 
</P>
<P>
 Reprise  
</P>
<P>
 * Times Line(TM): 808-8463. To hear an excerpt from "Seven Gates," call 
TimesLine and press * 5540 
</P>
<P>
 About the last thing you'd expect from an album co-produced by Neil Young is 
hushed spirituality.Yet that's just the tone this assemblage of rock, country 
and folk music veterans take in a collection of 13 holiday tunes, mostly 
standards. 
</P>
<P>
 For the uninitiated, project leader Ben Keith probably is best known as the 
steel guitarist who has played on many of Young's albums over the years. The 
list of participants ranges from Johnny Cash and Jack Clement to J.J. Cale and 
Pegi Young, Neil's wife, giving you the feeling that Keith phoned up his 
friends and put this together for the fun of it. 
</P>
<P>
 Hearing the Man in Black sing "Little Drummer Boy" is no big surprise, given 
his strong Christian faith -- the surprise is the duet vocal supplied by Young. 
And who'd ever have thought the Man in Plaid would one day record his version 
of "Greensleeves"? Then again, "What Child Is This?" isn't a far cry from the 
expression of awe in the presence of a miracle in Young's timeless Buffalo 
Springfield song "I Am a Child." 
</P>
<P>
 Keith doesn't depend exclusively on his guests for highlights. His own steel 
leads sweetly melancholy instrumental readings of Schubert's "Ave Maria" and 
Jean Villard's "Les Trois Cloches." 
</P>
<P>
 A nicely understated addition to the ever-swelling ranks of holiday 
recordings. RANDY LEWIS 
</P>
</TEXT>
