<HEADLINE>
<P>
PRO FOOTBALL DAILY REPORT; AROUND THE NFL; LAST-PLACE TEAMS LOSE AN ADVANTAGE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Last-place teams in each NFL division, which used to get a somewhat softer 
schedule than others, will play a schedule similar to their division opponents 
next season. 
</P>
<P>
 That is the main change in the new schedule format, released by the NFL, to 
accommodate the debuts of Carolina and Jacksonville next season. 
</P>
<P>
 Under the new format, the schedule for the first- and second-place teams in 
each division will remain the same. But the schedule for the next three teams 
will be accommodated to include fifth-place teams. 
</P>
<P>
 Under the old format, fifth-place teams played the other fifth-place team from 
its conference twice and had one game each against the fifth-place team from 
the other conference. Its other four nondivisional games were against the teams 
in the four-team conferences -- the AFC Central and NFC West. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Atlanta Falcon defensive end Chuck Smith (sprained right knee) will be 
sidelined for Saturday's game against Arizona. Smith, the team leader in five 
defensive categories, including sacks with 11. . . . Tampa, Fla., civic leaders 
unveiled a plan to guarantee home attendance of 55,000 per game for the 
Buccaneers' new owners. The team is for sale and could be moved. . . . Browning 
Nagle will start at quarterback for the Indianapolis Colts against the Buffalo 
Bills. . . . Charges against Cincinnati Bengal running back Derrick Fenner 
stemming from a confrontation with police outside a bar Dec. 11 were dropped, 
according to broadcast reports in Cincinnati. 
</P>
</TEXT>
