<P>
WEST VALLEY FOCUS: WOODLAND HILLS; FREE JOB-TRAINING COURSES OFFERED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MAKI BECKER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 As part of a federal effort to help economically disadvantaged people prepare 
themselves for the job market, Pierce College in Woodland Hills is offering 
free job-training courses for residents of both the city and county of Los 
Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
 Applications are now being accepted for enrollment next semester. 
</P>
<P>
 Courses offered include office administration, animal care-taking, certified 
nursing assisting/home health care, and automotive technology. 
</P>
<P>
 Workshops in interview and resume skills are also offered. 
</P>
<P>
 The city's portion of the program is for those ages 16 through 21, while the 
county's portion is open to both youths and adults, said Kathy Oborn, project 
director for the city. 
</P>
<P>
 Oborn said that after training people for jobs, the program helps them find 
work and checks up on them afterward. 
</P>
<P>
 "We can't just get them a job," Oborn said "We have to do follow-ups." 
</P>
<P>
 For information on applying to the program, call Oborn or Rachelle Cohn at 
(818) 719-6453. MAKI BECKER 
</P>
