<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS FOCUS: SOUTH COUNTY; TRAINING PROGRAM FOR LITERACY TUTORS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By FRANK MESSINA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 You don't have to be an English major to sign up as a tutor for the South 
Coast Literacy Council. 
</P>
<P>
 Anyone with a command of English will be accepted to instruct people from a 
wide variety of countries. 
</P>
<P>
 Knowledge of a foreign language is not required to take an 18-hour course, 
which starts Jan. 5. After graduation, tutors will teach speaking, reading and 
writing to small groups of one to three adults. There are 15 locations in South 
County. 
</P>
<P>
 The training program will take place on six consecutive Thursdays from 7 to 10 
p.m. at 31 W. Yale Loop in Irvine. Training is free, but prospective tutors are 
asked to pay $25 for their learning materials. 
</P>
<P>
 South Coast tutor Mary FitzGerald said she has grown to love the job after 
volunteering as a tutor for the past eight years. 
</P>
<P>
 "I just see the response we get from our students, and I just want to provide 
more tutors, because the need is never-ending," she said. 
</P>
<P>
 The group is part of a national organization called Laubach Literacy Action, 
based in Syracuse, N.Y. The South Coast Literacy Council covers the entire 
South County area and Irvine. 
</P>
<P>
 For more information, call (714) 458-8664 or (714) 493-3800.FRANK MESSINA 
</P>
</TEXT>
