<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEST VALLEY FOCUS: CALABASAS; STUDENT FOOD FIGHT HELPS THE HUNGRY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By FRANK MANNING 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Students at Calabasas High School waged a ferocious food fight on campus for 
two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
 But they weren't throwing food. They were collecting it to see who could 
gather the most items for the needy. 
</P>
<P>
 The friendly rivalry has become a tradition for students and their homeroom 
teachers, who face off each year to see whose students can collect the most 
food, said Jonathan Oringher, a senior. 
</P>
<P>
 Teachers go all out to win the competition, which this year lasted from Dec. 5 
to 15, Jonathan said. "One of the English teachers stored all the cans in 
cabinets, so nobody knew how much his class had." 
</P>
<P>
 Lee Shagin, who teaches U. S. government, won the contest, according to the 
Calabasas High School Student Council, which organized the drive. His students 
collected 3,042 items of food. 
</P>
<P>
 The school collected 9,491 items in all, apparently breaking a record, 
according to the council. In second place was Lorraine Meyer, a senior English 
teacher whose students collected 2,051 cans. Anna Blount, a Spanish teacher, 
came in third with 1,539 items. 
</P>
<P>
 Students collected the food from their homes, neighbors, friends and 
supermarkets. The food goes to a Los Angeles-based organization called Love Is 
Feeding Everyone (LIFE), which distributes food to the needy. 
</P>
<P>
 The activity serves a two-fold purpose in that it helps the needy and 
introduces students to volunteer work, said Lindsay Weissbach, a senior. 
</P>
<P>
 "When I was a 10th-grader, we had a similar competition, with good results," 
she said. 
</P>
<P>
 "We went door-to-door asking for cans and it really got people involved and 
enthused." 
</P>
<P>
 She said that activity inspired her so much that she joined with two other 
students, Traci Craig and Jennifer Wan, to form Interact, part of a nationwide 
student organization dedicated to helping charitable causes. 
</P>
<P>
 Calabasas Interact, which is affiliated with the Calabasas Rotary Club, has 
helped out at the Calabasas Days Pumpkin Festival. 
</P>
<P>
 Members have also donated time to such causes as the Rotary's Thanksgiving 
Senior Citizen Luncheon and the city's "Let It Snow" day. FRANK MANNING 
</P>
</TEXT>
