<HEADLINE>
<P>
TOY GUN 'PROTEST' AT CITY HALL DRAWS FIRE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JON GARCIA, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Pool hall owner Jerry Jamgotchian says bringing a toy gun to Hawthorne council 
meetings and repeatedly pulling the trigger was his symbolic protest of Mayor 
Larry Guidi's firing of a handgun in public in October. 
</P>
<P>
 But city officials say that type of protest is not appropriate in council 
chambers, and City Clerk Daniel D. Juarez has asked City Atty. Glen Shishido to 
look for legal ways to keep toy guns out of City Hall. 
</P>
<P>
 Juarez sent a memo to Shishido after he spotted Jamgotchian playing with a 
small gun during a Dec. 12 council meeting. According to the memo, Jamgotchian 
was "cocking the hammer of the gun and depressing the trigger" repeatedly. The 
gun was aimed at Guidi, Juarez said. 
</P>
<P>
 Jamgotchian said he paid about $2 for the bright orange plastic cap gun at a 
local toy store. He brought it to the meeting to call attention to an Oct. 27 
incident in which Guidi fired his 9-millimeter handgun into the air to scare 
off three juveniles who were breaking into a neighbor's car. 
</P>
<P>
 "Guidi wants to cover up his own gun escapade and wants people to forget about 
it," Jamgotchian said. "We need to make sure that people remember that what he 
did was criminal." But Guidi, who was cleared by police in the incident, was 
not amused by the protest. 
</P>
<P>
 "How do we know that was a plastic gun?" he said. "I get a lot of threats 
anonymously. I fear for my safety." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Guidi said he was unaware of the toy gun until after the meeting, but he said 
the incident has led him to question the security measures at City Hall. 
</P>
<P>
 "When I'm on a public street, I take my life into my own hands, but in the 
council chambers I should be protected," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 No uniformed police officers regularly attend council meetings, but Police 
Chief Stephen R. Port said the chambers are safe. Port, who attends most 
regular meetings and sometimes carries a handgun, said bringing a toy gun to 
the meetings is not illegal as long as council members are not distracted.  
</P>
<P>
 "If they are distracted, that conduct could be called out of order and 
(Jamgotchian) could be ejected," Port said. 
</P>
<P>
 Guidi said he is considering seeking a restraining order against Jamgotchian. 
</P>
</TEXT>
