<TEXT>
<P>
 Pentium formula -- The formula that can be used to determine whether a 
computer has a flawed Pentium chip is (4,195,835 x 256) (3,145,727 256).The 
correct answer, rounded off, is 87,413.3. When the formula is calculated on a 
computer with a flawed Pentium and with software that uses the computer's 
floating point function, it will incorrectly yield 87,407.9. Due to a 
typographical error, a story in Wednesday's editions gave an incorrect digit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
